    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Spending My Birthday in Anilao - the Posh Way]]></title>
    <link href="http://www.ensamiasien.se//blog/2015/11/05/spending-my-birthday-in-anilao-the-posh-way/"/>
    <updated>2015-11-05T06:03:14+01:00</updated>
    <id>http://www.ensamiasien.se//blog/2015/11/05/spending-my-birthday-in-anilao-the-posh-way</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>To celebrate my birthday last week me and Gen decided (in last minute) to get
ourselves to <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/WHWhTyUWMyr">Anilao</a>. A popular macro diving
site located only &ldquo;three hours&rdquo; away from Manila. Three hours Filipino time that
is. You probably can make it in three hours if you decide to go with a private
transport, however if you go with the local transport including a bus ride,
a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeepney">jeepney ride</a> and finally a
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auto_rickshaw_(Philippines)">tricycle ride</a>,
you&rsquo;re probably looking at 5 hours minimum.</p>

<!-- more -->


<p>There are several bus companies that does daily routes down to
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/dHCT6HNuhUR2">Batangas City</a>, we chose the one called
<a href="http://www.jam.com.ph/">Jam Liner</a> and paid roughly 125 php per person. When
you arrive at the bus station in
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/dHCT6HNuhUR2">Batangas City</a> you simply switch to one of
the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeepney">jeepneys</a> going to Mabini
(another 35 php per person). Be sure to tell the driver that you are going to
<a href="https://goo.gl/maps/WHWhTyUWMyr">Anilao</a> so he can drop you off at the
&ldquo;the crossing&rdquo; where you would continue the last part with a
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auto_rickshaw_(Philippines)">tricycle</a> for about
120 php.</p>

<p>Even though I&rsquo;m fully capable of carrying my own bag, this little kid insisted
on helping me carry my bag from the bus to the
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeepney">jeepney</a>. It was only about fifty meters
and I told him several times that I would carry my own bag. Around half way he
gave up, and I continued to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeepney">jeepney</a>.
Later when I was joking around with the jeepney-drivers the kid snuck up on me
and lifted my bag into the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeepney">jeepney</a>.
I laughed for my self and gave the boy some money. I would have loved to give
him credit for his quick-witted mind but he disappeared. I like to think that
this boy is going places if anybody just gave him the chance. Unfortunately the
world is tough and far from everyone gets the chance they deserve.</p>

<p>We arrived quite late to this resort called
<a href="http://goo.gl/rA4TyR">Halo Anilao Dive Resort</a> located far from the busy streets
life of <a href="https://goo.gl/maps/WHWhTyUWMyr">Anilao</a>. The resort itself isn&rsquo;t
anything special, I mean the rooms were nice and the food was good, but the
place it self was kind of &ldquo;meh&rdquo;. It kinda threw me off a bit, and we only stayed
there one night. The next day we decided to go all in and chose a place called
<a href="http://goo.gl/go2q74">La Chevrerie Resort &amp; Spa</a> (after all, my sister told me
to &ldquo;spoil myself&rdquo; since I&rsquo;m always so stingy, I however consider myself as an
economic person, I&rsquo;ll leave it up for discussion though).</p>

<p><a href="http://goo.gl/go2q74">La Chevrerie Resort &amp; Spa</a> is a fantastic resort in every
aspect, the rooms were amazing, the food was gorgeous, the view was stunning and
the staff was extremely helpful and friendly. The only thing I could say
something about is the price, but I guess you get what you pay for. And there
are far more expensive resorts out there, but yes,
<a href="http://goo.gl/go2q74">La Chevrerie Resort &amp; Spa</a> did leave some sort of whole
in my wallet ;)</p>

<p>The plan was to stay in the area for a couple of days, but we cancelled the
holiday since Gen&rsquo;s cat unfortunately passed away. Her name was
<strong>Ate Guy</strong> (pronounced &ldquo;ah-teh-guy&rdquo;) and we brought her to the veterinarian two
days earlier since she hadn&rsquo;t been eating for a while and was very weak. The
veterinarian did what they could and gave her antibiotics, but after two days
<strong>Ate Guy</strong> sadly passed away. Gen rescued <strong>Ate Guy</strong> from the streets about
seven years ago, during these years <strong>Ate Guy</strong> has had the best possible life.
I&rsquo;m sure <strong>Ate Guy</strong> has her place in cat heaven by now.</p>

